`

**WHAT DOES IT DO:**

**Secondary size reduction** - pulverizes coarse shredded fibers
(30-50mm) into fine fibers (3-8mm, target D50 ≈6mm). This is high-energy
impact milling to approach final 2mm target before screening.

**HOW IT WORKS (Impact Milling):**

1.  **Material Entry:** Coarse fibers from BC-06 drop into elevated feed
    hopper, gravity-fed into mill chamber

2.  **Rotor Impact:**

    -   High-speed rotor (1,200-1,800 RPM) with **32-48 swing hammers**
        mounted on pins

    -   Hammers are **free-swinging** (pivot on pins) - this is KEY
        advantage over fixed knives

    -   Material enters chamber → hammers strike fibers at high velocity
        (tip speed 50-80 m/s)

3.  **Repeated Impact:**

    -   Fiber particles bounce around chamber, struck multiple times by
        successive hammers

    -   Each impact **fractures fibers** into progressively smaller
        pieces

    -   Particles strike each other (particle-on-particle attrition) -
        additional size reduction

4.  **Screen Plate Retention:**

    -   Chamber bottom has **AR400 steel screen plate** with 8-10mm
        perforations

    -   Oversize material (\>8-10mm) cannot pass through → retained in
        chamber → continues to be hammered

    -   Undersize (\<8-10mm) passes through screen → discharges to BC-07
        conveyor

5.  **Discharge:** Fine fibers (3-8mm majority) exit mill via screen
    plate

**WHY SWING HAMMERS (vs. Fixed Knives):**

Your Stage-1 report: *\"Single broken hammer \$50, swap 30 min\"* - this
is critical economic advantage.

-   **Swing hammers:** If hammer hits metal (despite OBM-01 + MD-01),
    hammer **swings backward** on pivot → absorbs impact energy → may
    crack but doesn\'t shatter → **\$50 replacement, 30 min job**

-   **Fixed knives:** Metal impact → knife **rigidly mounted** → all
    energy transferred to blade → blade shatters → fragments damage mill
    housing/bearings → **\$5,000-\$15,000 repair, 2-3 days downtime**

**MACHINE SITS ON:**

-   **Reinforced concrete pad:** 3m L × 2.5m W × 0.6m thick with
    **heavy-duty vibration isolation pads** - hammer mill generates
    **highest vibration** of any machine in line

-   **Foundation must be separate from building columns** - vibration
    can crack structural concrete if directly coupled

**OUTPUT OF MACHINE:**

-   **Product:** Fine pulverized EFB fibers, 3-8mm (majority 5-10mm),
    target D50 ≈6mm, 47% MC

-   **Mass:** 6.9 t/hr (same as input - no moisture change during dry
    milling)

-   **State:** Dusty fine fibers ready for final 2mm classification
    screening

**FIRE RISK CONTROLS (CRITICAL - NON-NEGOTIABLE):**

Hammer mill generates **friction heat** (hammers striking fibers at
1,800 RPM) + EFB fiber dust is **combustible organic material**. This is
**highest fire risk point** in entire facility.

**Mandatory Controls:**

1.  **Dust extraction system:**

    -   200mm diameter flexible hose from mill discharge to central
        cyclone dust collector

    -   Creates **negative pressure** inside mill housing (-50 to -100
        Pa)

    -   **Interlock:** Dust fan MUST run whenever HM-01 runs (fan trip →
        mill stops automatically)

2.  **No dust accumulation:**

    -   Daily sweeping/vacuuming of floor around HM-01

    -   **Do NOT allow fiber dust \>5mm depth** on floor (combustible
        layer)

3.  

4.  **No smoking / hot work permits:**

    -   \"NO SMOKING\" signs posted in hammer mill area

    -   Welding/grinding near HM-01 requires **hot work permit** (fire
        watch, extinguisher ready, check for smoldering after work)

5.  **Fire extinguisher:**

    -   20 kg dry powder extinguisher mounted **within 5m of mill**,
        clearly marked

    -   Monthly inspection (pressure gauge check)

6.  **Operator training:**

    -   Monthly fire drill (practice using PASS method: Pull pin, Aim at
        base, Squeeze handle, Sweep)

    -   Know location of nearest fire alarm pull station

**Optional (higher cost):**

-   Spark detection system in discharge chute (infrared sensor detects
    sparks → triggers water spray suppression) - \$10,000-\$20,000

**OPERATOR SAFETY & MAINTENANCE:**

-   **Noise:** **Minimum 95 dBA at 1m** (engineering estimate) -
    **MANDATORY hearing protection zone** around mill (signage + PPE
    enforcement)

-   **Guards:** Full sheet metal enclosure with bolt-on access panels
    for hammer inspection/replacement

-   **Daily:** Visual inspection through access window (hammers rotating
    freely, no visible cracks), listen for abnormal noise (grinding =
    screen plate blockage or bearing damage)

-   **Weekly:** Hammer wear inspection via access panel (mill stopped) -
    measure hammer thickness with calipers, if worn \>50% of original →
    replace

-   **Monthly:** Screen plate inspection (check particle size
    distribution of output - if \>20% oversize, screen may be blinded or
    worn)

-   **Quarterly:** Complete hammer set inspection, bearing temperature
    check (IR thermometer), drive belt condition

-   **Annual:** Replace ALL hammers (preventive, even if not fully
    worn), screen plate replacement, bearing replacement

**Critical Spares:**

-   Swing hammers (individual): Keep 20 on-site (≈50% of total),
    \$50-\$80/hammer, lead time 3-4 weeks from Malaysia

-   Screen plate (replaceable): Keep 2 on-site, \$800-\$1,500/plate,
    lead time 6-8 weeks, 3-6 month life

-   Main shaft bearings (set of 2): Keep 1 set on-site, \$1,200-\$2,000,
    lead time 6-8 weeks

**Hammer Replacement Procedure (30 minutes):**

1.  Stop mill, lock-out/tag-out

2.  Open access panel (remove 4× bolts)

3.  Remove retaining pins from rotor shaft

4.  Slide old hammer off shaft

5.  Slide new hammer on, reinstall pins

6.  Close panel, remove lock-out

7.  Restart mill

**No rotor removal required** - hammers replaced individually while
rotor stays in mill.

